prefix_rule(pattern=["jq", "--null-input", "--arg", "inReplyTo", "PRRC_kwDOAQkeGc7DY8iW", "--arg", "body", "Also, `ItemMarshaller.toItem(Item(id, name))` is hard to read because `Item` is both the test domain class and the DynamoDB request field concept. Could we rename the marshaller method in the example to something like `toDynamoItem(...)`? That would make the call site read as `item = ItemMarshaller.toDynamoItem(Item(id, name))`, which is clearer about the conversion boundary.", "{query: \"mutation($input:AddPullRequestReviewCommentInput!){addPullRequestReviewComment(input:$input){comment{id databaseId url body}}}\", variables: {input: {inReplyTo: $inReplyTo, body: $body}}}"], decision="allow")
prefix_rule(pattern=["jq", ".data.repository.pullRequest.reviewThreads.nodes[] | select(.path == \"jvm-dynamo/src/test/kotlin/aff/dynamo/testing/TestingDynamoDbModuleIntegrationTest.kt\" and .line == 43)"], decision="allow")
prefix_rule(pattern=["jq", "--null-input", "--arg", "inReplyTo", "PRRC_kwDOAQkeGc7DY4TW", "--arg", "body", "Also, `ItemMarshaller.toItem(Item(id, name))` is hard to read because `Item` is both the test domain class and the DynamoDB request field concept. Could we rename the marshaller method in the example to something like `toDynamoItem(...)`? That would make the call site read as `item = ItemMarshaller.toDynamoItem(Item(id, name))`, which is clearer about the conversion boundary.", "{query: \"mutation($input:AddPullRequestReviewCommentInput!){addPullRequestReviewComment(input:$input){comment{id databaseId url body}}}\", variables: {input: {inReplyTo: $inReplyTo, body: $body}}}"], decision="allow")
prefix_rule(pattern=["jq", "--null-input", "--arg", "reviewId", "PRR_kwDOAQkeGc8AAAABAkU0PQ", "--arg", "commitOID", "7bde6ad774130a02412b2c3932341b732494d543", "--arg", "path", "jvm-dynamo/src/test/kotlin/aff/dynamo/testing/TestingDynamoDbModuleIntegrationTest.kt", "--argjson", "position", "53", "--arg", "body", "`ItemMarshaller.toItem(Item(id, name))` is hard to read because `Item` is both the test domain class and DynamoDB’s request-field concept. Could we rename the marshaller method in the example to something like `toDynamoItem(...)`? That makes the conversion boundary clearer at the call site.", "{query: \"mutation($input:AddPullRequestReviewCommentInput!){addPullRequestReviewComment(input:$input){comment{id databaseId url path line body}}}\", variables: {input: {pullRequestReviewId: $reviewId, commitOID: $commitOID, path: $path, position: $position, body: $body}}}"], decision="allow")
prefix_rule(pattern=["jq", ".data.repository.pullRequest.reviews.nodes[] | select(.state == \"PENDING\" and .author.login == \"galkk\") | .comments.nodes | sort_by(.createdAt) | .[] | {id:.databaseId, path, line, body, url, createdAt, updatedAt}"], decision="allow")
prefix_rule(pattern=["mkdir", "-p"], decision="allow")
prefix_rule(pattern=["/bin/zsh", "-lc", "gh api repos/Affirm/all-the-things/pulls/191770/reviews/4333057085 --method PUT --field body=$'I like the goal of making `jvm-dynamo` thinner and closer to the AWS SDK, but I do not think the current schema layer is the right tradeoff.\\n\\nThe place where this should pay for itself is `jvm-test-kotlin-dt/db/src/main/kotlin/aff/testKotlinDt/db/dynamo/TestKotlinDtDynamoDao.kt`, and the call sites still look awkward. `getPerson`, `deletePerson`, and `updatePerson` still pass `personTableName` into raw SDK calls. `queryPersons` and `getPersonsByLastName` still write raw key-condition expressions and raw `AttributeValue` maps. `putPerson` and `transactPutPersons` still manually choose when to call `PersonMarshaller`.\\n\\n`PersonMarshaller` is still useful: it gives us one explicit conversion boundary and avoids repeated item-map construction. But it does not justify the schema abstraction by itself. The DAO still has to use raw SDK calls, raw table names, raw expressions, raw GSI query wiring, and manual update expressions.\\n\\nSo `MappedSchema` mostly buys dev/test table creation plus `keyOf(...)`, while adding a parallel schema model that does not cover marshalling, expressions, updates, transactions, GSI query ergonomics, migrations, or normal typed access patterns. This feels close to territory AWS itself is already moving into with its Kotlin mapper APIs. I do not think we should create our own middle layer unless we are willing to own a full mapper-shaped abstraction. Right now this is more than a thin wrapper, but much less than a real typed mapper.\\n\\nI would rather simplify the PR in this direction:\\n\\n1. Keep `PersonMarshaller` / `ItemMarshaller` as the explicit conversion boundary between Kotlin models and DynamoDB item maps. That is the useful part: one place for `toDynamoItem` / `fromDynamoItem`, instead of repeated map construction.\\n\\n2. Drop or greatly narrow the schema abstraction. If table creation is only for dev/test/thor, let that code use DynamoDB\\'s own request model directly. I do not think we should introduce a public parallel schema model unless it materially improves production call sites or owns a real table lifecycle story.\\n\\n3. Fix the Kotlin model instead of hand-writing `equals/hashCode`. `Person` can use value-equality types like `List<Byte>` / `Set<List<Byte>>`, and the marshaller can convert to/from the SDK\\'s `ByteArray` shape at the Dynamo boundary. That gives consumers a proper example to copy instead of fragile, error-prone custom equality/hashCode code.\\n\\n4. If we want a declarative schema/model layer, I think that should be a separate design: property references, annotations, generated schemas, or something mapper-shaped. I am happy to prototype this separately, but I would not mix a partial version into this PR.\\n\\nMy recommendation: keep this PR focused on the thin client, instrumentation, retry/pagination helpers, and explicit marshalling examples. Remove or narrow the parts that look like a half-step toward a custom mapper/schema framework.'"], decision="allow")
prefix_rule(pattern=["/bin/zsh", "-lc", "gh api graphql -f query='mutation($reviewId:ID!, $body:String!) { updatePullRequestReview(input: {pullRequestReviewId: $reviewId, body: $body}) { pullRequestReview { id databaseId body } } }' -f reviewId='PRR_kwDOAQkeGc8AAAABAkU0PQ' -f body=$'I like the goal of making `jvm-dynamo` thinner and closer to the AWS SDK, but I do not think the current schema layer is the right tradeoff.\\n\\nThe place where this should pay for itself is `jvm-test-kotlin-dt/db/src/main/kotlin/aff/testKotlinDt/db/dynamo/TestKotlinDtDynamoDao.kt`, and the call sites still look awkward. `getPerson`, `deletePerson`, and `updatePerson` still pass `personTableName` into raw SDK calls. `queryPersons` and `getPersonsByLastName` still write raw key-condition expressions and raw `AttributeValue` maps. `putPerson` and `transactPutPersons` still manually choose when to call `PersonMarshaller`.\\n\\n`PersonMarshaller` is still useful: it gives us one explicit conversion boundary and avoids repeated item-map construction. But it does not justify the schema abstraction by itself. The DAO still has to use raw SDK calls, raw table names, raw expressions, raw GSI query wiring, and manual update expressions.\\n\\nSo `MappedSchema` mostly buys dev/test table creation plus `keyOf(...)`, while adding a parallel schema model that does not cover marshalling, expressions, updates, transactions, GSI query ergonomics, migrations, or normal typed access patterns. This feels close to territory AWS itself is already moving into with its Kotlin mapper APIs. I do not think we should create our own middle layer unless we are willing to own a full mapper-shaped abstraction. Right now this is more than a thin wrapper, but much less than a real typed mapper.\\n\\nI would rather simplify the PR in this direction:\\n\\n1. Keep `PersonMarshaller` / `ItemMarshaller` as the explicit conversion boundary between Kotlin models and DynamoDB item maps. That is the useful part: one place for `toDynamoItem` / `fromDynamoItem`, instead of repeated map construction.\\n\\n2. Drop or greatly narrow the schema abstraction. If table creation is only for dev/test/thor, let that code use DynamoDB\\'s own request model directly. I do not think we should introduce a public parallel schema model unless it materially improves production call sites or owns a real table lifecycle story.\\n\\n3. Fix the Kotlin model instead of hand-writing `equals/hashCode`. `Person` can use value-equality types like `List<Byte>` / `Set<List<Byte>>`, and the marshaller can convert to/from the SDK\\'s `ByteArray` shape at the Dynamo boundary. That gives consumers a proper example to copy instead of fragile, error-prone custom equality/hashCode code.\\n\\n4. If we want a declarative schema/model layer, I think that should be a separate design: property references, annotations, generated schemas, or something mapper-shaped. I am happy to prototype this separately, but I would not mix a partial version into this PR.\\n\\nMy recommendation: keep this PR focused on the thin client, instrumentation, retry/pagination helpers, and explicit marshalling examples. Remove or narrow the parts that look like a half-step toward a custom mapper/schema framework.' --jq '.data.updatePullRequestReview.pullRequestReview | {databaseId, body}'"], decision="allow")
